0.body: Disclaimer : this specification is going to change a lot as the language evolves. It is still a very new project and nothing is set in stone yet. The koj language was born as a side project of mine after taking a class on compilers for my second year at TELECOM Nancy.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: The goal for the syntax of this language is for it to be as consistent as possible. Each syntactic construct should have one function and one function only.
1.title: Syntax

10.body: Integer literals represent an integer value. They can be written in decimal, hexadecimal, octal or binary notation. INTEGER_LITERAL := DECIMAL_LITERAL | HEXADECIMAL_LITERAL | OCTAL_LITERAL | BINARY_LITERAL DECIMAL_LITERAL := DEC_DIGIT* HEXADECIMAL_LITERAL := 0xDEC_DIGIT+ OCTAL_LITERAL := 0oOCT_DIGIT+ BINARY_LITERAL := 0bBIN_DIGIT+ BIN_DIGIT := [0 - 1] OCT_DIGIT := [0 - 7] HEX_DIGIT := [0 - 9 a - f A - F] DEC_DIGIT := [0 - 9]
10.title: Integer literals

11.body: Floating-point literals represent a floating-point value. They can be written in decimal or hexadecimal notation. FLOATING_LITERAL := | DECIMAL_LITERAL . DECIMAL_LITERAL? | . DECIMAL_LITERAL | DECIMAL_LITERAL (. DECIMAL_LITERAL)? EXPONENT EXPONENT := (e|E) (+|-)? DECIMAL_LITERAL
11.title: Floating-point literals

12.body: Character literals represent a single character. String literals represent a sequence of characters.
12.breadcrumbs: Lexical Structure » Literals » String and character literals
12.title: String and character literals

13.body: CHAR_LITERAL : ' ( ~[ ' \ \n \r \t] | QUOTE_ESCAPE | ASCII_ESCAPE | UNICODE_ESCAPE ) ' QUOTE_ESCAPE : \' \" ASCII_ESCAPE : \x OCT_DIGIT HEX_DIGIT | \n | \r | \t | \\ | \0 UNICODE_ESCAPE : \u{ HEX_DIGIT[1,6] }
13.title: Character literals

16.body: Tokens can be one of the following elements, described it the previous chapters : Keywords Identifiers Literals Punctuation
16.title: Tokens

17.body: This chapter describes the grammatical structure of the language.
17.title: Grammatical Structure

18.body: There are 4 main types of declarations : type declarations, variable declarations and function declarations. For the sake of consistency, all declarations start with the keyword let.
18.title: Declarations

19.body:
Syntax TypeDecl : let type TYPE_IDENTIFIER = Type ; Type declarations can be used both to alias existing types or create new ones. The identifiers on the right-hand side of an equal sign, the right-hand side of the colon in struc fields and in enums must correspond to existing already types. Example: You can define a Pizza type representing a recipe for a pizza in the following way: let type Pizza = struct { .crust: enum `Thick | `Thin | `Cheesy; .base: enum `Tomato | `Cream; .toppings: [string];
}
19.breadcrumbs: Grammatical Structure » Declarations » Type Declarations » Type Declarations
19.title: Type Declarations

2.body: The first iteration of this language is going to be implemented using an interpreter written in Ocaml, using sedlex as a lexer and menhir as a parser. This language may then evolve to be a compiled one, probably implemented in itself with a hand-written lexer and parser and leveraging LLVM as a backend.
2.title: Implementation

20.body: Syntax Type : TYPE_IDENTIFIER | PrimitiveType | ArrayType | FunctionType | Struct | Enum | InferredType
20.title: Type System

21.body: Koj offers these different primitive types:
21.breadcrumbs: Type System » Primitive Types » Primitive Types
21.title: Primitive Types

22.body: This type represents an integer value. It is represented by the identifier int.
22.breadcrumbs: Type System » Primitive Types » Integer type
22.title: Integer type

23.body: This type represents a floating point value. It is represented by the identifier float.
23.breadcrumbs: Type System » Primitive Types » Floating point type
23.title: Floating point type

24.body: This type represents a single character. It is represented by the identifier char.
24.breadcrumbs: Type System » Primitive Types » Character type
24.title: Character type

25.body: This type represents a text string. It is represented by the identifier str. For more info on these types, see literals
25.breadcrumbs: Type System » Primitive Types » String type
25.title: String type

26.body: Syntax ArrayType : [ Type ] Array types represent a sequence of elements of the same type. They are dinamically sized.
26.breadcrumbs: Type System » Array Types » Array Types
26.title: Array Types

27.body: Syntax FunctionType : ( ( Type ( , Type )* )? ) -> Type Example: A function adding two integers together may have the following type: (int, int) -> int
27.breadcrumbs: Type System » Function Types » Function Types
27.title: Function Types

28.body:
Syntax Struct : struct { StructFieldDec + } StructFieldDec : . TYPE_IDENTIFIER : Type ; Structs are used to represent objects with fields. They are analogous to structs in C or record types in languages such as OCaml. Example: You may create a struct representing a point in 2D space the following way: struct { .x: int; .y: int;
}
28.breadcrumbs: Type System » Struct Types » Struct Types
28.title: Struct Types

29.body: Syntax Enum : enum |? EnumMember ( | EnumMember )* EnumMember : ` TYPE_IDENTIFIER ( EnumMemberOfType )? EnumMemberOfType : ( Type ) Examples: To represent a direction on a D-pad, you could use the following enum: enum `Up | `Down | `Left | `Right To represent a user on a website, you could use the following enum: enum | `Anon | `LoggedIn(struct { id: string; role: string; })
29.breadcrumbs: Type System » Enum Types » Enum Types
29.title: Enum Types

3.body: This chapter describes the lexical structure of the language. Input Format Whitespace Comments Keywords Identifiers Literals Punctuation Tokens
3.title: Lexical Structure

30.body: Syntax InferredType : _ This type is used to let the compiler infer the type of the item.
30.breadcrumbs: Type System » Inferred Type » Inferred Type
30.title: Inferred Type

4.body: The input format of the koj language is a sequence of Unicode code points encoded in UTF-8. The input is read from a file or from the standard input.
4.breadcrumbs: Lexical Structure » Input Format » Input format
4.title: Input format

5.body: The koj language uses the following whitespace characters: ' ' (U+0020 SPACE) '\t' (U+0009 CHARACTER TABULATION) '\n' (U+000A LINE FEED) '\r' (U+000D CARRIAGE RETURN) U+000B LINE TABULATION U+000C FORM FEED U+0085 NEXT LINE U+200E LEFT-TO-RIGHT MARK U+200F RIGHT-TO-LEFT MARK U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR These characters are called whitespace characters and are used to separate tokens in the language. They are not part of the language and are ignored by the lexer. The meaning of the program is preserved if any whitespace character is replaced by another one.
5.title: Whitespace

6.body: Comments are used to document the code and are ignored by the compiler. There are two types of comments: Single-line comments start with // and end at the end of the line. Block comments start with /* and end with */. They can span multiple lines. COMMENT := LINE_COMMENT | BLOCK_COMMENT LINE_COMMENT := //[^\n]* BLOCK_COMMENT := / *.*?* /
6.title: Comments

7.body: The following keywords are reserved by the koj language: KW_AS: as KW_BREAK: break KW_CATCH: catch KW_CONST: const KW_CONTINUE: continue KW_DO: do KW_EACH: each KW_ELSE: else KW_ENUM: enum KW_FALSE: false KW_FOR: for KW_FUNC: func KW_IF: if KW_IS: is KW_LET: let KW_MATCH: match KW_MUT: mut KW_RETURN: return KW_STRUCT: struct KW_THROW: throw KW_TRUE: true KW_TRY: try KW_TYPE: type KW_UNION: union KW_WHILE: while This list may change as the language evolves. There keywords are reserved and cannot be used as identifiers.
7.title: Keywords

8.body: Identifiers are represented by the regular expression [a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*. They are used to name variables or functions names. They may not be one of the keywords described previously. Type identifiers are similar, but they must start with a lowercase letter. The corresponding regular expression in [A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_]*
8.title: Identifiers

9.body: Literals are used to represent values in the source code. They are used to initialize variables, to pass arguments to functions, etc.
9.title: Literals
